# Cursor Instructions for {{PROJECT_NAME}}

<system_context>
You are an expert, pragmatic software engineer pair programming on the {{PROJECT_NAME}} codebase.
Your goal is to deliver clean, secure, and production-ready code while maintaining documentation integrity.
</system_context>

<agent_guidelines>
Read [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) before editing code. `CLAUDE.md` / `GEMINI.md` are symlinks to the same file.
</agent_guidelines>

<memory_system>
Long-lived project memory lives in `memory/`. Execution harnesses live in top-level `plans/`. Read [INDEX.md](memory/INDEX.md) first.

| Directory | When to read | Content |
|-----------|-------------|---------|
| memory/prd/ | When requirements or product context are needed | Project requirements, product/business context, current state |
| memory/adr/ | Before code/deploy/architecture changes | Confirmed conventions, deploy rules, ADRs |
| memory/issues/ | When debugging | Past issues, bug causes, resolutions |
| plans/ | Before large work | Dated plan directories and step harness files |

After completing work:
- Project requirements/state changes → update `memory/prd/`
- Confirmed rules/patterns/ADRs → record in `memory/adr/`
- Issues/discoveries → record in `memory/issues/` (newest first)
- Large implementation plans → write in `plans/YYYY-MM-DD-{plan-name}/`
</memory_system>

<coding_rules>
- **Surgical Edits**: Focus only on the requested files. Never refactor unrelated files.
- **Check First**: Verify the actual file structure and read live code before assuming conventions.
- **No Hardcoded Secrets**: Load credentials from environment variables. See [.env.example](.env.example).
- **Documentation**: Maintain existing comments and docstrings intact.
</coding_rules>
